description.text:
Darth Maul sculpted in ZBrush then retopologised his head in Maya to make a clean split between black and red for multi color printing. This was a one week project.

To substantially preserve materials on support, both arms were split and pins/keys were added to connect them to the body later.

Head printed separately with a dual extruder printer using black and red filaments.

Lightsber were split to print its parts in red and silver filaments.

Printer:

CreatBot DE PLus 3

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.16 - 0.2

Infill:

5% - 20%

Notes:

This is a 300mm in height model. If you want to scale it down, I'd recommend combining all parts first and scale them down together, then separate them again.

I didn't get good result printing the head with less than 0.16 resolution.

Also, my dual head extruders are not perfectly aligned as a note, this is why I got a slight offset in the red color which is the second extruder.

To align and merge the black and red head parts in Simplify 3D:

  1. Import both parts
  2. Select them both and group them
  3. From Edit menu, click on Align Selected Model Origins

In Cura:

  1. Import both parts
  2. Assign a color to each part
  3. Click on Merge
When gluing the lightsber parts, if the 3 pieces are not perfectly straight, don't worry. Just wait until the glue is dry then blow it with a hairdryer and make it straight gently.

title: Small Clamp for Modular Clamping System

description.text:
This is a small clamp that plugs into a weighted base as part of a modular clamping system. To make this, you'll need:
1 x 1/4-20 2" carriage bolt
1 x 1/4" nut
5 x No. 0 (4 x 1/2) wood screws

You can find the base here:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2759738

The clamp has replaceable jaws to fit different objects. Currently these include:

  • A flat jaw (https://www.thingiverse.com/download:4562734)
  • A jaw with a small 2 x 4 mm clamping area (https://www.thingiverse.com/download:4568331). This comes in two pieces that you glue together.
  • A jaw to hold small cylindrical pieces horizontally (https://www.thingiverse.com/download:4568330)

The clamp opens to about 28 mm, depending on the kind of jaw you use. A Fusion 360 file with the jaw template is included.

To Assemble

1) Slide the round, flat bit on the "clamp knob" into the slot in the back of the "clamp body" so that the central holes line up. Slide the carriage bolt through the holes on both pieces.

The fit between the carriage bolt head and the inside of the knob should be snug, so make sure that the square section at the base of the bolt head is lined up with the square socket inside the knob before you try to press it in.

2) Fit the "knob cap" into the knob such that the screw holes line up. Secure the two pieces together with one No. 0 wood screw.

3) Put the 1/4" nut into the slot at the back of the "clamp slider" and slide it into the bearing surface of the clamp body until it reaches the threads of the carriage bolt. Screw it into place.

4) Screw the "clamp base" to the clamp body by screwing four No. 0 wood screws in the plugs on the four corners.

NOTE: the screw heads will tend to force the walls of the bottom plugs apart, making for a tight fit into the sockets of the weighted base. Don't overtighten them. If the fit is too snug, file the outer edges of the sockets back slightly. The upside is that, if the edges wear until the fit is too loose, you can just tighten down the screws to restore the fit.

This is a prosthetic hand design, "Gripper Palm Remixed V.G3D" which uses Torsion Spring.
You can make use of Gripper palm with Spring for your own Use.

Gripper Thumb Terminal Device Originally made by Skip has been Remixed and worked out to improve functionality. As in the original design, O-ring is used which was failing when multiple actuations were made and it did not return to its original position as well.
We tried using multiple O-rings but it did not have enough strength to withstand.

So I along with my team decided to remix the functionality part. The design is great and more natural looking so it makes recipient easily adapt to it.
We modified the Thumb and the Palm, where we made space for using Torsion Stainless Steel Spring ( Wire:2mm diameter, Inner Diameter: 7mm) locally fabricated, also we used a piece of Mild Steel rod (4mm Diameter) to keep the spring at the place. This provided us with much better actuation and grabbing force.

Plug is also modified, Skip had made a separate plug that attaches to the gripper palm. The idea of this model is to make a spiral object like a vase, but also useful.
I used cura engine on repetier host, and for the red and green translucent PETG i seted a temperature of 220°C , a shell thickness of 1 mm, a Top/Bottom thickness of 1 mm, and spiralize contour in general extruder setting. I changed the nozzle with a 0,8 mm nozzle and seted layer to 0,3mm.

This clip is to attach a Right Angle Finder to the polar scope of a Skywatcher Star Adventurer tracking mount. The photographs show the original version of this clip, I have since updated it to be more robust.

I designed it to work on my Neewer RA Finder but it could possibly work with similar ones (that have the removable adaptor plates for various camera types). My finder came with a few different adaptor plates and I chose the metal screw-together type which was labeled for use with the older Nikon F series cameras. As you can see from the photos, this just screws into the printed clip allowing you to leave it in place on the Polar Scope but remove the RA Finder easily. It is best oriented with the clips at the top and bottom (rather than on the side).

I have also included a printable version of the adaptor plate for those of you that don't have the metal one that came with my finder. This is in separate parts so that you can print them without any support and glue together to give the right slot thickness for your RA finder. However, please note that this has not yet been tested (as of 19th Jan) but I may do so in the future. There are images that show how this should go together with the inner washer in place first so that the outer parts sit in their correct positions.

I hope that you find it useful, but use at your own risk.

title: Motor Pinion M1 (Modulus 1) T14 with M3x5 Screw Grub

description.text:
Hi There! I own a OpenRC Truggy and modifyed it to use a Mod1 Central Differential. I had troubble to find out a Mod1 pinion with 3.17mm bore and i had to search for an adaptor.

I'm planning to build my second printed RC car and now cant find the adapter to use 5mm bore metal pinions in 3.17 motor shafts.

So i gave a try to this Modulus Gear Customizer and the result i think is very good!

I substracted a cylinder from the exported customizer stl to be able to use a screw grub to lock the pinion in its position. The substracted cylinder was 2.8mm diameter and was good for me to strongly fit the screw grub.

I have given full throttle from 0 and full brake from "top speed" to see if the pinion can do it's work without easyly breaking and there it is :) Also with the 1.1 KG extra weight of my FJ Cruiser Body!!!

The creator of the modulus Customizer included 2 params to create a keyhole, but not a screw grub hole. It would be nice if he does, so we could directly create the final stl file for printing just in the customizer!

Anyway if you need some help to get a pinion similar to mine but with a different number of teeth just say something! :)

Notes:

The accuracy of both holes is very important. The shaft hole is 3.2mm in diameter, so if your printer makes it a little smaller try to use some drill or something to make the shaft fit with no pressure.

My Anet A8 is not much accurate. I use to print with -0.05 horizontal expansion but this time i did not. The 2.8mm hole worked perfect for a strong M3 scew grub, but the 3.2mm shaft hole was small for me with no horizontal expansion, so i used a dremmel flat drill bit (3.2mm) to re-shape the hole and it worked perfectly!!!

comments.text: I do like the parts by 3DFreezeMe, but all the arguments about 3 points defining a plane, etc are irrelevant in this situation because the wheels are not adjustable anyway. I think 4 wheels are better in this case because it will more tightly constrain the X axis gantry bar in the same amount of space. Equal belt tension is a big factor is keeping the x axis gantry bar square as well. I personally feel like the Mega gantry plates are obnoxious overkill - and I also don't like the single bearing tower on the Mega plates. The single bearing tower idea is good for cancelling the front to back stresses, but it doubles the stress on the bearing tower towards the center. Not a good trade-off... I think your design combines the best of all considerations. Thanks!

description.text:
In honor of Magic: The Gathering's Ixalan block, I made a themed deck box!

I'm all about that Ixalan pirate booty, so nothing seemed more appropriate than a good ol' fashioned iron-bound treasure chest, with some dinosaur claws and teeth for extra flavor. It's a bit more complicated than my previous Amonkhet-themed box, with 21 separate pieces and a more intricate "lock". Rotate the ship's wheel (which doubles as a 1-20 life counter) and pull the sword out to unlock your deck.

It should hold up to a 100 card, single-sleeved EDH deck. I'll probably include a custom spacer as well in a bit so it holds a 60 card deck nice and snug, as well as a sideboard, but we'll see. I also plan on changing the sword out for a model of the actual Pirate's Cutlass. Check back in... a week?

The prototype I made (and is pictured) is a bit more "mixed materials." I'd suggest grabbing leather straps (or fake leather) and real cloth for stuff like the flag or the claw, but I've included models so you can print the entire flag and "leather straps" if you want.

Everything but the Flag and Chest Bottom will need some supports, but I tried to optimize it so no exposed surface will have supports touching it. For the hinges, you should use the rivet method. 1.75mm filament fits very well.

(UPDATE(13.MAR.2013.):
There will be a H4 soon. I'm not sure when but I'm working on it. In the meantime I would be grateful for any and all info about your experience with it so far via PM either here or on the new Ultimaker forum. I hope that will make the next one even better and more user friendly. Thanks!) After many trials and errors here is my new extruder for the Ultimaker. It has some nice features namely: -spring loaded bearing idler, based on Bertho's excellent design
-integrated bowden clip
-quick release system to pull out the entire gear/bearing/bolt assembly
-fliplock for very easy opening and closing without the need to release tension in order to open (something that seriously bugged me on the stock extruder, when I needed a lot of tension for a certain filament, the thing wouldn't open until I released the thumbscrew) Take a look at the following videos to see how it looks: http://youtu.be/17JNsZ7IKTU
http://youtu.be/Yb96mQMyrVk Tested and working with the UM V2 bolt, Arcol.hu's hyena bolt and my KNRLR spiked bolts. -UPDATE 05.OCT.2012-
A small change is necessary in the bearing axle part to make it more rugged, it's usable as it is but will deteriorate after a month or two of use. The best thing would be to use a 12 mm metal rod cut to 5mm thickness and drill a M3 hole in it. Or you can print spares and use that. I will try to design a new, tougher axle now and post results. -UPDATE TWO 05.OCT.2012-
Solution found! Scratch the metal rod part. It's not exactly 12 mm and drilling a hole is a hassle. Get 3 M5 washers, they are round 11.8mm OD. Superglue them together. Take two normal m3 nuts and tape one or two loops of blue tape around them, cut off the excess width of the blue tape. Push that into the hole in the washers. And there you have it, a 5 minute all metal axle! :) Enjoy. -UPDATE 07.OCT.2012.-
Added experimental kit for using the Ultimaker V3 bolt. Instructions will be updated soon. For some reason the UM mount was mirrored, so it's been updated with the right version.

Please see attached H3 Instructions.pdf for all info. 
As I see it, the H3 is finished. I tested it extensively and I'm satisfied, so I'm removing the work in progress tag. 
There may be updates in the future (mainly a new mount) but I don't plan on making big changes. 
I am always open for suggestions and fixes so if anybody tests it and has some ideas, please let me know.

description.text:
After designing my single Amazon Dash button, I realised that I wanted a group of three buttons next to each other and created a case for that. Then I realised that I could chop up the original model to get a modular design that can be stuck together on the computer for two or more Amazon Dash buttons! Here is a ready-to-print version made using it that holds two Amazon Dash buttons.

There are ready-to-print single and triple button versions and the modular page is here

It's designed to be used either with the sticky pad included (and used to stick it to the inside back of the case) or you will need to use a mm thick spacer/foam pad to hold it in place. The back holds in place purely with friction as long as you don't take it off and put it on too many times. I left a bit of additional space around the outside of the dash to allow for shrinkage of different printers, so if the dash isn't stuck in with double-sided tape or similar it will rattle around.

It's ideal to stick onto a wall etc next to whatever you want to control/order. I use alternate versions at home that can hold multiple Dash buttons (see remixes) where I've cut an icon for whatever it controls into the case as I don't use them to actually order things from Amazon, but to talk to a Raspberry Pi listening for the broadcast when they connect to my network!

I created it in Solidworks and included those files as well as the STLs for printing. The case is 3.2mm thick as I found that any thinner with my printer with it's 0.4mm nozzle the inside and outside of the wall separate.

Notes:

Print however you like with whatever quality. The higher the better. It's designed to be printed with no supports/raft, but you MAY get some issues with the fillet depending on your printer (I haven't). You will have to join the bits together in 3D design software before printing unless you are planning on gluing them together afterwards!

Well, here's a start to something that might float your boat. The little brother of the Replicator, or the result of a one night stand between an Ultimaker and a Replicator. I've taken the Replicator files (at this point, just the frame really) and chopped off the lengths by ~5" and lowered the interior base by ~10mm for some more Z travel (could probably take off even more).

title: Razor Blade Caddy
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Basic caddy for standard single-edge utility razor blades. I got sick of the "free" thin PET plastic case that comes with every 100-count package of razors popping open and spreading loose blades all over my tool chest. This caddy is designed with just enough clearance to allow blades to fit easily, but not enough for them to slop and rattle around. Ends are slotted and inner dividers are lowered to allow easier removal of packed blades. Dividers are spaced so as to not allow the last blade in a segment to fall flat and be a pain to remove.

Base is pocketed for easier removal from build plate. However, there are two versions of this model: one with a chamfer around the base to aid removal and deal with "Elephant's Foot"; and another with "Mouse Ears" at the corners and no base bevel, to improve edge bed adhesion when printing high-warp materials, such as ABS/ASA and Nylon.

Tri errors reported in KISSlicer where FreeCAD performed the pocketing for the end-slots have been fixed in updated models. Bug in FreeCAD causes overlapping coincident pockets to cause triangle error when exporting. Adjusted pocket reference points, and now everything is peachy.

I didn't like the stock fan setup on the Tevo Tornado so I started looking for ideas to change it and I found what I was looking for with this thing: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2160958
The CR-10 and Tornado are very similar and share the same mounting holes/screws on the X-gantry, only difference is the heatsink is a little wider on the Tornado. So I tried printing superpotatofudge's design only cutting off the 'wings' so that it sits flush on the heatsink. It worked but it wasn't ideal. The mounting plate on the print is too thick to use the stock screws and it sat off center so most of the air just blew around the heatsink.

So I took inspiration from his design and made my own specifically for the Tornado. It's not the most beautiful and certainly not aerodynamic, but it directs all the air from the fan to go through the cooling fins on the heatsink, and not all over the hotend like the stock setup. It goes without saying you lose the part cooling fan, but that hasn't been an issue for me yet.

Anyway, maybe someone will find this helpful if you don't like the stock setup. Thanks bye.

description.text:
After designing my single Amazon Dash button case, I realised that I wanted a group of three buttons next to each other and created a case for that. Then I realised that I could chop up the original model to get a modular design that can be stuck together on the computer for two or more Amazon Dash buttons! Here it is.

There are ready-to-print single, double and triple button versions.

It's designed to be used either with the sticky pad included (and used to stick it to the inside back of the case) or you will need to use a mm thick spacer/foam pad to hold it in place. The back holds in place purely with friction as long as you don't take it off and put it on too many times. I left a bit of additional space around the outside of the dash to allow for shrinkage of different printers, so if the dash isn't stuck in with double-sided tape or similar it will rattle around.

It's ideal to stick onto a wall etc next to whatever you want to control/order. I use alternate versions at home that can hold multiple Dash buttons (see remixes) where I've cut an icon for whatever it controls into the case as I don't use them to actually order things from Amazon, but to talk to a Raspberry Pi listening for the broadcast when they connect to my network!

I created it in Solidworks and included those files as well as the STLs for printing. The case is 3.2mm thick as I found that any thinner with my printer with it's 0.4mm nozzle the inside and outside of the wall separate.

Notes:

Print however you like with whatever quality. The higher the better. It's designed to be printed with no supports/raft, but you MAY get some issues with the fillet depending on your printer (I haven't). You will have to join the bits together in 3D design software before printing unless you are planning on gluing them together afterwards! I've also printed the other way up using grid supports autocreated in Cura with no issues.

Use these holders to easily place servos onto robotic dioramas or other displays made of cardboard. The rivet parts come from user hooligan404's cardboard rivets, which we use a ton in our K-8 makerspace!

Servos can either be held horizontally such that an extender like a popsicle stick could stick into your diorama and move a character from side to side, or held vertically such that you could pull a string on a pulley or move a character up and down. The holders can be placed on the sides, back, top, or bottom of a box and hold the servo steadily in place! See the short video for examples by 2nd graders.

The larger holders are sized to hold servos like the Hitec HS-311 (https://www.amazon.com/Hitec-31311S-HS-311-Standard-Universal/dp/B0006O3WVE) and the smaller ones sized to hold 9g micro servos like the Tower Pro SG90 (https://www.amazon.com/J-Deal-Micro-Helicopter-Airplane-Controls/dp/B015H5AVZG/).

We've used with our Hummingbird robotics kits (https://hummingbirdkit.com/), as well as with cheap, simple ATTiny-driven robots (https://twitter.com/HuffmanJeannine/status/696132761329926144).

title: X-Carriage with smaller distance between bearings

description.text:
After printing some X motor holders/ idlers and carriages (in this case what holds the bearings), I have found that the distance between bearings never matches exactly. I’m guessing it is because the parts are being printed in different orientations (vertically for the holder/idler and horizontally for the carriage).

The distance difference is really small, about 0.3mm, but it is surprisingly enough for the carriage to force the smooth rods apart and make the x movement not smooth, but forced. Which is not good.

To solve this, I remixed (starting from zero) the beautiful design of @MazaaFin in his/her “Smooth X-axis for Prusa i3” and I made the distance between the bearings 0.3mm shorter. As I said, it’s a very small difference with a very big effect. By using this design my carriage got a very nice and smooth movement.

I designed this part in Onshape and everyone is free and welcome to have a look and modify it to his/her needs. By changing the indicated variable, you can easily modify the inter-bearing distance.

description.text:
NA Flute bird:

There are many NA (Native American) style flute designs on the web, with a wide variety of materials and techniques. While far from ‘traditional’ designs, the easiest format for youthful experiment is to use 3/4” PVC Schedule 40 plastic plumbing tubing with drilled holes for finger stops and the sound system. Complete directions are available at https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=misjPOhd-9o

The PVC can be handled with a small saw, some tape, a ruler and a drill press (or hand drill) using a sharp pencil. However, the air holes have to be carved to final dimension with a small, sharp hobby knife, which is not suitable for working with youngsters, like camp or craft demos. Also, this format requires a small wooden “bird” that redirects the air from one air hole and forms it into a ‘laminar air flow with some Bernoulli compression’.

The bird gives a flute that does not depend on careful lip placement or muscle control. Birds can be carved in soft wood (pine, cedar, basswood) with a very sharp 1/4” chisel and a lot of careful work. However, many characteristics of the flute depend on the bird and some very small dimensions. As you play, it absorbs moisture from your breath, which is one more variable. The bird is placed and tied with tight wraps of string, but it is still easy to move around and break.

Sounder:
One issue with this flute design is cutting the sharp edge in the lower air hole of the sounder section. If you could simply drill the 2 holes and glue in a 3D printed sounder, the need for sharp knives is almost eliminated! This is especially attractive for crafting flutes in camp craft settings!

Use the HF center drill set (item #60381) that will drill a 3/16” and 1/2” diameter holes into the plastic. Drill the small size into pencil marks that are exactly 20 mm apart (55 mm and 75 mm from the end of the flute), then enlarge with the 1/2” drill. Very light pressure is required and the bits have almost no flutes to spin the plastic tube (or drill thru the other side of the tube).

Notes:

The sounder does not need infill, but should be printed with support. The bird works best with 20% infill, and support is not required. Keep the speed down on your printer and filament temperature at the low end of acceptable melt range, after the first layer.

For PLA, you may need to print 3 or 4 on one plate, to allow the small pieces to cool properly.

Flute bird:
With 3D printing and 0.4 mm nozzles, we can simply print a simple plastic bird, or print 20 for a group instruction session! The bird is printed upside down, so we get the best smooth surface on the inside of the air channel. There are small layer marks that can be removed with a few LIGHT strokes on some 220 grit sandpaper on a tabletop, but do not sand more than necessary to just get a smooth seal surface. A piece of sandpaper can be rolled to shape the other side for comfort and appearance. The design includes a depressed area for wrapping the string. A couple of drops of instant set (CA) glue will hold the bird securely, after initial tuning.

The bird can be ABS or PLA, and both seem to work well. ABS is slightly more flexible, which is not desirable. My best results have been with PLA+ and you may need to print 3 or 4 at a time, so the PLA has time to cool between layers.

Sounder:
Use HF center drill set (item #60381) to drill a 3/16” and 1/2” diameter holes into the plastic. Drill the small size into pencil marks that are exactly 20 mm apart (55 mm and 75 mm from the end of the flute), then enlarge with the 1/2” drill. Very light pressure is required and the bits have almost no flutes to spin the plastic tube (or drill thru the other side of the tube).

The sounder needs to be cleaned on the inside so that it will mate closely to the pipe. It is helpful to scrape the outer edge of the pipe holes, to taper the fit. A piece of a wine bottle cork is cut to the distance between the 1/2” hole edges and pushed into the flute tube. The sounder is gently pressed onto the pipe, noting the hole with the angled edge is in the lower hole, then a bird is held at the top of the lower vent hole and sound is tested. It is important to avoid pressing on the lower hole with your finger, or the angled edge will bend and the sounder will not work. Some may need the ramp and edge to be trimmed slightly, to smooth the ramp and make the upper edge of the hole very sharp.

Once the sounder is verified to work, a small amount of glue can be spread inside the sounder. Also spread a small amount of glue around each hole, then gently press the sounder in place and tie with a few wraps of string, until it hardens. After removing the string, a bird can be placed and adjusted for easiest play, then it can be glued and tied until hard.

Close-up photos show the parts as printed in PLA. Printing direct to the heated plate forms a fairly sharp edge, so do not trim anything from the edge with a ramp (indicated by the pointer) until you test the sounder. Install the cork in the PVC pipe, with a drop of glue into any holes in the cork stopper. Despite some air leakage, the sounder needs only the blobs and burrs removed inside the saddle area. After testing, you can either glue it to the PVC pipe, or use some warm beeswax smeared inside the saddle as a sealant. Sand and finish the sounder, then experiment with position of the bird for best tone and easy operation. I glue the bird in place, but you may prefer a small amount of beeswax painted along the bottom of the bird, then tie it in place with string or wet leather lace.

These are much more difficult in ABS or with nozzles larger than 0.4 mm!

The bird in ABS is fairly effective, but you need to have extrusion factor set to give a very smooth upper surface in the air channel. You can improve it with a bit of acetone on a cotton swab, to smooth the channel, but do not wipe to the very edge. The bird depends on a flat front surface and a very square edge on the air channel.

description.text:
My second upload to thingiverse - a Playing Card Box that I printed as a christmas gift for my dad (an avid Bridge player)

A friend bought some playing cards with extra large symbols for a grand parent, but the cards came without a box. I volunteered to design and print a box for the cards. It turned out so beautiful that I decided to print a couple more to give to my parents as well :D

I wanted a snug fit to the cards so I just added a millimeter or two on the inside to the box. I went for an even tighter fit between the box with the actual lid so I designed it without any spacing what so ever. This means that you probably need 2-3 minutes of sanding on the surface that connects with the lid depending on how well calibrated your printer is. I prefer it this way since you can decide yourself how tight of a fit you want.

To make sure it could be opened easily I put a spacing of a couple of mm between the lid and the box so that your fingers has something to grab a hold of when pulling it apart. It also makes the design look so much better.

I uploaded two versions, one for poker cards (88x62.5x17.7mm) and one for bridge cards (89x58x16.5mm). The inside spacing is ~1mm on each side of the length and width of the cards if I remembered correctly. The height is a lot tighter though, only 0.1mm for the poker version, and I recon something similar for the one bridge version. It all depends of course on how many extra cards your deck comes with (jokers and such).

If you want to customize it yourself or change anything, you can find my OnShape design here:
https://cad.onshape.com/documents/ee55f5835ab2c350ce528559/w/50aeca0ba31a97960b171323/e/9b75e2508b18c5f25f958a88

The spade symbol is not created by me, but I converted and imported it to OnShape in order to use it.

description.text:
This simple design does a great job as a business card dispenser / holder.

Conventional business card holders / boxes / dispensers lean the cards backwards which makes the top edge of the front card you want to get out lower than those behind it. The net result is removing 'a single' card is difficult and you usually end up pulling out several then have to put all but one back.

This is where this design differs...

While the cards placed in the Business Card Dispenser angle back wards very slightly the surface they are sitting on is angled far more steeply. This makes the front cards top edge sit above all the others behind it... just gently rest your finger on the top edge of the front card and roll the card forward. It should move away as the single card you want leaving the rest untouched and in place.

The Business Card Dispenser also looks a bit quirky and different from a 'normal' card holder plus being 3D printed adds a novelty value.

Great to use yourself or as a simple little gift. Print in your / someone's favourite color or keep it simple and subtle.

Made to work with regular landscape business cards 90mm x 55mm

This is a simple print but please refer to the images and print setting instructions for additional information. And, please post images of your Business Card Dispenser in use for other members to see.

This is a super easy print with no support required. However, raft is recommended to ensure good build plate adhesion due to the thin contact area of the lower edge with the build plate.

Great to use yourself and as a unique gift for almost anyone. And, they look great printed in any colour. At standard scale the Fidget Ball Container is 75mm in diameter, so has a surprising amount of space inside, but it can be uniformly scaled up / down to suit your storage needs (just not too small or the wall thicknesses will become too thin and weak).

The fun part is that it rolls around but can be balanced by the weight of the things being stored inside it. This lets you change the position of the things inside (i.e. shake around etc.) which will change the position / location of the opening. It can point straight up or be over on it's side. Tap it and you can wobble it or spin it around. You can have lots of fun fidgeting with this and it also has a practical purpose.

Please refer to the images and print setting instructions for additional information. And, please post images of your Fidget Ball Containers in use for other members to see.

Note: If you like this check out the rest of my practical and fun designs.

title: VR gun stock for HTC Vive (v2)

description.text:
This is a complete redesign of bigwoody003's fine stock which I needed to hack down to fit my 12 x 12 cm printer bed. I simplified it for easier printing and remade the cups to precisely fit the HTC Vive wands. I also beefed up the sliders. I didn't make any Rift cups, but the ones from bigwoody's design should fit as the stocks share the same top rail (or just make his new Uber stock instead, which looks pretty awesome tbh).

I think this stock feels good and solid and the cups fit perfectly, allowing you to easily slide the wands out to reload or throw a grenade, without being loose enough for them to wobble. The butt end was just a placeholder, but it works well enough and the flat design allows you to position the stock higher or lower on your shoulder depending on the weapon. The geometry of the stock is optimized for the Marsoc AK5C and Volk G3, but works with all weapons except the PKM (the off-hand grip in game is too far forward to reach). If you really like the PKM you could print a 5th rail piece to make it longer, but then it would be a pita to switch to a sub-machine gun. I didn't test the shotgun or the P90.

There are holes for #8 bolts to secure the pieces together, but I just glued them instead (you can see where gorilla glue expanded and oozed out on the butt piece; bad choice - I used crazy glue for the rest and it's much cleaner looking and stronger). The sliders can be held in position with #8 nuts and bolts as well, although I just wrapped mine with hockey tape instead. The sliders have a tight fit and almost stay in place without it. I never move them.

description.text:
Designed for use with the 60mm Noctua NF-A6 series fans.
Ultimate cooling! Ultimate Silence!

The optional probe mount accepts probes with 8mm outside diameter. A longer M3x0.5 screw may be required. be sure to clip the tab at the bottom of the probe mount, it is only there to make printing easier

In fact, there is so much cooling you can make the fan even quieter by using one of the Low-Noise Adapters that Noctua includes with their FLX fans.

This fan duct was designed to use the anti-vibration mounts which come the Noctua fan but the model has accommodations to allow M4 screws to be used instead (there is a thin layer of plastic capping M4 sized holes under the channels for the Noctua mounts).

Print the included gasket in TPU (and mount it under the fan) to stop air leaking around the anti-vibration mounts while maintaining effective vibration dampening. The gasket could also be printed in PLA and used to stop air leaks but clearly a PLA version won't provide vibration dampening or you could forgo the gasket entirely as the airflow should be more than enough without it.

description.text:
Have you ever desired an accurate Graflex Blade plug to be springy like the actual movie prop?

Well lucky for you, I've created that very thing!

Made specifically for a 1 inch Thick Walled Polycarbonate tubing. Which you can source from an old blade you've owned or buy a lone 40" tube from The Custom Saber Shop: http://www.thecustomsabershop.com/1-Thick-walled-Polycarbonate-40-long-P150.aspx

You'll also need a compression spring that fits inside slot. I advise to visit your local hardware store and juggle around the different springs that suit your preference.

In the post-printing section, there's a video demonstrating the spring in action!

Printer:

Tevo Trantula

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.1mm

A majority of the post process is going towards the Pin. I found that chucking it onto a drill can make the sanding portion move a lot faster as you can simply have the drill turning and with a coarse grit, you'll be able to remove a majority of the print lines.

Get the pin a decent smoothness and after that, you're set to paint.

Painting is fairly easy, the top and bottom bits should be done in a satin black. As for the pin, I used an antique gold but I think a pure gold would work better. I experimented with the paint application and left the pin in the drill and just applied the gold onto the surface. By doing that, I got a faux brushed kind of finish.

Apply a few coats of the gold to get a nice lookin' piece.

After that, it's just a matter of gluing the top and bottom into the tube. I used Loctite Super glue for the bottom piece but noticed it fogged up the tubing. It's not noticeable since the plug is hidden within the Emitter, but still.

Use an epoxy or E6000 to adhere the parts. Cut your spring to size and drop it into the slot. (The best length is to have the spring just barely escape the lip of the Bottom part.) Apply the glue onto the top piece around the OD and the bottom lip, (IE the thicker ring.)

Stick the pin on top the spring, and slip the top through the pin and press it down onto the tube until the parts lay flush.

Glue is cured and boom! You have your own Springy Graflex Blade plug~

description.text:
This base and capacitor is used in a physics lab that explores charging of capacitors and in which students calculate the value of the capacitor.

I created this base to hold the capacitor and to allow connecting it into a circuit using banana plugs. Before this we were just using "alligator" clips and I found the capacitors legs would end up getting bent over and over. The capacitance seemed to change, posibly because of the stress placed on the leads. This relieves the stress and is just more elegant and makes loosing the caps a little more difficult.

I made the bases stack so that they are easy to store. They fit side by side and stack 3 high in a standard 6" wide cardboard storage bin.

Parts

The capacitor is a 4700uF 16V Aluminum Electolytic with a 20% tolerance.

  • Digi-key (Canada) part number 1572-1162-ND.

The banana plugs are simple short versions to keep the height down.

  • Digi-key (Canada) part number J151-ND (Red).
  • Digi-key (Canada) part number J152-ND (Black).

Assembly

  1. First install the red and black banana plugs (Red in the "+" and Black in the "-"). I put a dab of glue gun glue on the nut once installed just to make sure it stays put.
  2. Bend the legs of the capacitor such that the value written on the capacitor is hidden when the capacitor is mounted. I gave the leads a nice round bend with my fingers.
  3. Make sure you have the polarity right and then use a glue gun to glue the capacitor in place. E6000 hobby glue also works and gives you more time to pull the cap out when you accidentally put it in backwards.
  4. If you didn't feed the leads through the banana plug's hole (It is designed to line up perfectly) then just wrap it to the post and solder in place.

Notes

The way the stl displays on Thingiverse is not how I printed it. Flip it onto it's other edge for best results and no support.

If I ever print another large batch of these, I might make them a little shorter so that I can fit a fourth row of them into 6" storage bin. (It's just fluke that they fit so nicely side by side).

I might also add a small bump to the inside of the legs that mates with the top when stacked to that they stay together better when stacked in a cupboard. Right now they do tend to clip onto each other because of the way the legs bend towards each other ofter the print cools.

description.text:
"The HUM Box V1" (Prototype Version)

The HUM Box is a creation of inspiration, picked up from the (H)ypercube-(U)ltimaker-Ivan (M)iranda Printers, and offcourse our own Tinkered version of the Ivan Miranda printer.

....This is a Finished working prototype....
....Printvolume 200x200x230....
....All parts are printed in PLA....
....First photo gives a View from the finished Prototype....

Once you created The HUM Box and dialed it in, you will notice that there is almost no need to re-adjust the level of the bed.
Neither is there a need for dual Z-endstops or a bed leveling sensor due the sturdy bed / frame build.

Be aware, Building the frame precise (equal lengths) and square (90 degrees angles) is mandatory on the success of your printer.

The reason we created The HUM Box:
We were not satisfied with the results of the Tinkered Ivan Miranda 300mmx300mmx500mm build, it's a nice printer as long as you don't go over the height limit of about 250mm. If you do, change the build to minimum 30x30 extrusions, better even 40x40.
Also a very high amount of Z-Wobble that almost can not be reduced.

Notes for The HUM Box V1:
Keep in mind that there is a lot of plastic used as we printed all parts with 100% infill, used filing / sanding / grinding / etc to come to the end prototype models in the design.
We kept the adjusted prototype printed parts on the printer but adjusted them digital.
Still, all parts look like the prototype, the parts are not optimized yet to use a minimum of plastic.

Future enhancements:
This most likely will come in an upgraded version, The HUM Box V2 (Optimized V1 printed parts).
Possible change in the X- and Y Carriages, holding a Chimera Hotend, running on a MKS 1.4 or MKS 1.5 and mounts for 40x40mm fans so we can use Noctua fans to reduce the noise even more.
Plans are also already on the table to create The HUM Box V2-L / The HUM Box V2-XL (2019/2020 or sooner if we have the time)

Print suggestion:
The 100% infill is not needed if you want to make The HUM Box, all up to you.
Most parts will do with 20 to 40% infill, 3 parameters, 4 top and bottom layers, at 0.2 layer height. All depends how sturdy you want to make it.

Print the "Mk2 Heat Bed Bracket" and the "Z T-Nut Bracket" or "Z M8-Nut Bracket" on 100% infill to avoid bending by tension.

Be sure to have the correct settings on your printer, all depends on your calibration and filament you use, print a square and circular calibration tower first so you can measure with your parts.
We happened to have a 2.3Kg spool of filament that had a 3.5% crimp factor.

We assume you have a perfect calibrated printer with the filament you use.
You swap filament and suddenly the dimensions are not correct anymore.
Two things you can do:

  1. Re-calculate the steps and adjust them accordingly in for example Marlin and flash the eeprom, retest, rins and repeat till it is correct again. (To much of a hassle)
  2. Calculate the percentage deviation on the filament crimp.

How to calculate the percentage deviation:
Formula to use: 100*(measured value-old value)/old value = percentage deviation

So for example after using the square tower:
The square extrusion will not fit in 20.5, meaning the new value is 20.6
The Deviation is then 100*(20.6-20)/20 = 3%.
This means that your filament has a 3% crimp.
Take your measurements in account and add the percentage in your slicer software when printing the parts. (Done)

Alignment of the Z-Axis Supports:
Use "X-Axis Bracket Front clamp 1.0" to align the Z-Axis support on top and bottom, alignment taken from the front of the printer with 0.5mm space between the bracket and Z-Axis supports. Align those parts first before placing the bottom box. You can flip the bracket 180 degrees to use on the right hand side.

Notes on the build:
Be sure that the Z-Axis rods have a snug fit in the Z-Axis supports.
All brackets that needs to be placed over the square extrusions of the frame, need to have a tight fit, though not need to be placed with the use of force.

For the print bed.
All brackets need to have a loose fit, but without any play
if your brackets for the heatbed have a snug fit, you can do the following trick to get them on a loose fit.
Slide the bracket over a piece of extrusion of about 100mm. This probably will need a bit of force to get them on, be sure that the bracket is about in the center of the extrusion.
Now get yourself a soldering iron and place it inside the extrusion and let it heat up.
Be patient and careful as the extrusion will get hot. Best is to use a towel to hold the extrusion when you start working on the bracket.
If the extrusion and the printed part reach the desired temperature, you will be able to start sliding the bracket over the extrusion.
Remove the soldering iron, switch it off and put it away on a safe spot.
Remove the bracket from the extrusion, let it cool down a bit, it will cool down faster then the extrusion, then place it back on the extrusion to slide it a few more times.
You should now have a loose fit without the need of using a file or sanding.
If you need to apply to much force to get the bracket on the extrusion, file it down first as it will not work with the above trick.
When assembling the bed frame, as shown on the first picture of the printer, the Mk2 Heat Bed Bracket 1.0 needs to be mounted at a 9.2mm distance from the Z Axis Bearing Holder 1.0. On the side where the Dual axis NEMA sits.

description.text: Took the awesome conversion kit and added a receptacle for the tubes that came with my Flashforge. Also included is just the tube extension if you want to print it and glue it to the original.

I shouldn't have to say it but... Use these at your own risk.

I designed this to allow for easy customization of your grips, hopefully there will be some cool medallion remixes coming from the rest of the community. I hope to post some more medallions soon too.
I recommend using epoxy when placing your medallion in the grip to ensure it will hold up to live fire.
Hope you like it.

Printer Brand:

Up!

Printer:

Up Mini

Resolution:

finest

Infill:

finest
I left the exterior bevel on the detail a little tall so that the grips could be well sanded for a smooth feel. Sanding isn't necessary but recommended.

Remixed this to have thicker walls on some files for scaling, separated the files for hassle free printing, all you need to do is rotate them so the base of each part is flush to the print bed. make 5 small jewels and one large.

First print everything, then paint it with acrylic. Next get dental floss, a sewing needle, and a comfortable but cheap glove to attach everything to. I got some small earth magnets to attach the jewels with. You can use hot-glue to help attach the parts to the glove, but sewing the parts on is the best way I found to ensure attachment.
I repaired the original file with http://www.makeprintable.com to thicken some of the walls, then I separated all of the files on http://www.tinkercad.com for easy printing.
